.TH _PRINTF 3 "January 2026" "Holberton Project" "Library Functions Manual"
.SH NAME
_printf \- custom formatted output function

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.sp
.B int _printf(const char *format, ...);

.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf
function prints formatted output to the standard output stream.
It takes a format string and a variable number of arguments,
similar to the standard C
.B printf
function, but with limited functionality.

The format string consists of ordinary characters and conversion
specifiers, which begin with a percent sign (%).

Supported conversion specifiers are listed below.

.TP
.B d, i
Print a signed decimal integer.

.TP
.B c
Print a single character.

.TP
.B s
Print a string of characters. If the argument is NULL,
the string "(null)" is printed.

.TP
.B %
Print a literal percent sign.

The following features are not supported:
.RS
- Flag characters
- Field width
- Precision
- Length modifiers
- Any conversion specifiers other than those listed above
.RE

If the format string is NULL, the function returns -1.
If a percent sign is followed by an unsupported specifier,
the percent sign and the character are printed as-is.

.SH RETURN VALUE
On success,
.B _printf
returns the number of characters printed, excluding the null byte.
On error, -1 is returned.

.SH EXAMPLES
Print an integer and a string:
.RS
.nf
_printf("Value: %d, Name: %s\n", 10, "Test");
.fi
.RE

Print a percent sign:
.RS
.nf
_printf("Completed: 100%%\n");
.fi
.RE

Print a character:
.RS
.nf
_printf("Grade: %c\n", 'A');
.fi
.RE

.SH SEE ALSO
printf(3)

